<body>

<div class="cover-page">
    <div class="cover-title">LocalHub</div>
    <div class="cover-subtitle">Hyperlocal Service Booking Platform<br>System Architecture & Design Document</div>
    <div class="cover-meta">
        <strong>Author:</strong> Lead Architect Agent<br>
        <strong>Platform:</strong> Spring Boot 3.x, Java 21, React (MUI), PostgreSQL<br>
        <strong>Date:</strong> July 2026<br>
        <strong>Status:</strong> Approved Specification
    </div>
</div>

<h1>1. Executive Summary</h1>
<p>LocalHub is an online marketplace designed to coordinate hyperlocal service transactions between customers and verified partners (plumbers, AC mechanics, TV repair professionals). The system matches requests using real-time geocoding data and enforces service boundary limits calculated dynamically on the server.</p>

<h1>2. System Architecture Design</h1>
<p>The application follows a decoupled three-tier architecture that segregates presentation layer dependencies from business logic and physical data tables:</p>

<h2>2.1. Presentation Layer (Frontend Clients)</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Client Mobile Portal:</strong> Single-page application optimized for mobile viewports, containing client order tracking, Wallet Top-Ups, and live partner mapping widgets.</li>
    <li><strong>Provider Mobile Portal:</strong> Integrated dashboard allowing partners to toggle status flags, claim active requests, manage localized GPS listings, and upload/publish custom offerings.</li>
    <li><strong>Admin Control Console:</strong> Desktop dashboard console used by system operators to verify partner documents and monitor platform transactions.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2.2. Application Logic Tier (REST Web Service)</h2>
<p>The web service layer is built on Spring Boot 3.x, executing within a Java 21 JVM. It contains security filtering pipelines, REST endpoint routes, and core database service transaction methods.</p>

<h2>2.3. Data Storage Tier</h2>
<p>Persistent transaction ledgers are stored inside a PostgreSQL relational database. Flyway database migration scripts execute sequentially on application startup to ensure schema consistency.</p>

<h1>3. System Component Mapping</h1>
<table border="1">
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Module Name</th>
            <th>Component Scope</th>
            <th>Primary Classes</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Authentication (auth)</strong></td>
            <td>JWT validation filters, user profile updating, WhatsApp OTP dispatch.</td>
            <td><code>AuthController</code>, <code>AuthService</code>, <code>JwtService</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Business Partner (business)</strong></td>
            <td>Partner verification statuses, location setups, business details.</td>
            <td><code>BusinessController</code>, <code>BusinessService</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Service Booking (servicebooking)</strong></td>
            <td>Service catalogs, order scheduling rules, proximity checks.</td>
            <td><code>BookingController</code>, <code>BookingService</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Financial Ledger (wallet)</strong></td>
            <td>Depositing balance, transactions processing, platform fee splitting.</td>
            <td><code>WalletController</code>, <code>WalletService</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><strong>Real-time Chat (chat)</strong></td>
            <td>P2P communication, media sharing, location coordinates sending.</td>
            <td><code>ChatController</code>, <code>ChatService</code></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

<h1>4. Database Entity Relationships</h1>
<ul>
    <li><strong>User Accounts (<code>users</code>):</strong> Stores core credentials, phone lines, role types.</li>
    <li><strong>Business Profile (<code>businesses</code>):</strong> Shop registry containing service coordinates, operations schedules, and checkbook states.</li>
    <li><strong>Service Catalog (<code>services</code>):</strong> Specific service offerings linked to provider profiles.</li>
    <li><strong>Appointments Ledger (<code>bookings</code>):</strong> Stores scheduling slots, customer target coordinates, active workflow states, and bill amounts.</li>
    <li><strong>Accounting (<code>wallets</code>):</strong> Ledger cards mapping cash values with split payment logs.</li>
</ul>

<h1>5. Key Feature Workflows</h1>

<h2>5.1. WhatsApp OTP Verification Flow</h2>
<p>To register or log in securely, users execute the following verification steps:</p>
<ol>
    <li>The client app initiates a POST request to <code>/api/v1/auth/otp/send</code>.</li>
    <li>The backend generates a cryptographically random 6-digit verification code.</li>
    <li>The code is stored as a hashed entry in the database with a 5-minute expiration window.</li>
    <li>The code is printed to server logs (simulating WhatsApp API dispatch).</li>
    <li>The user inputs the code, calling <code>/api/v1/auth/otp/verify</code>. If matches, the database marks the phone line as verified.</li>
    <li>The registration payload is submitted containing the OTP, completing user account setup.</li>
</ol>

<h2>5.2. Hyperlocal Distance Calculation</h2>
<p>All service coordinates are verified on the server using the <strong>Haversine Formula</strong> to determine the distance in kilometers between the customer and provider:</p>
<pre>
double latDistance = Math.toRadians(customerLat - providerLat);
double lonDistance = Math.toRadians(customerLng - providerLng);
double a = Math.sin(latDistance / 2) * Math.sin(latDistance / 2)
        + Math.cos(Math.toRadians(customerLat)) * Math.cos(Math.toRadians(providerLat))
        * Math.sin(lonDistance / 2) * Math.sin(lonDistance / 2);
double c = 2 * Math.atan2(Math.sqrt(a), Math.sqrt(1 - a));
double distance = R_EARTH_KM * c;
</pre>
<p>If the distance exceeds the provider's defined service boundary radius, booking creation throws a validation exception to ensure operators only serve local customers.</p>

